#. Tag: para
#: index.docbook:24
#, fuzzy, no-c-format
#| msgid ""
#| "Data URLs allow small document data to be included in the URL itself. "
#| "This is useful for very small HTML testcases or other occasions that do "
#| "not justify a document of their own."
msgid ""
"Data URLs allow small document data to be included in the &URL; itself. This "
"is useful for very small &HTML; testcases or other occasions that do not "
"justify a document of their own."
msgstr ""
"Data URLs allow small document data to be included in the URL itself. This "
"is useful for very small HTML testcases or other occasions that do not "
"justify a document of their own."

#. Tag: para
#: index.docbook:28
#, fuzzy, no-c-format
#| msgid ""
#| "<userinput>data:,foobar</userinput> (note the comma after the colon) will "
#| "deliver a text document that contains nothing but <literal>foobar</"
#| "literal>"
msgid ""
"<userinput>data:,foobar</userinput> (note the comma after the colon) will "
"deliver a text document that contains nothing but <literal>foobar</literal>."
msgstr ""
"<userinput>data:,foobar</userinput> (note the comma after the colon) will "
"deliver a text document that contains nothing but <literal>foobar</literal>"

#. Tag: para
#: index.docbook:33
#, fuzzy, no-c-format
#| msgid ""
#| "The last example delivered a text document. For HTML documents one has to "
#| "specify the MIME type <literal>text/html</literal>: <userinput>data:text/"
#| "html,&lt;title&gt;Testcase&lt;/title&gt;&lt;p&gt;This is a testcase&lt;/"
#| "p&gt;</userinput>. This will produce exactly the same output as if the "
#| "content had been loaded from a document of its own."
msgid ""
"The last example delivered a text document. For &HTML; documents one has to "
"specify the &MIME; type <literal>text/html</literal>: <quote><userinput>data:"
"text/html,&lt;title&gt;Testcase&lt;/title&gt;&lt;p&gt;This is a testcase&lt;/"
"p&gt;</userinput></quote>. This will produce exactly the same output as if "
"the content had been loaded from a document of its own."
msgstr ""
"The last example delivered a text document. For HTML documents one has to "
"specify the MIME type <literal>text/html</literal>: <userinput>data:text/"
"html,&lt;title&gt;Testcase&lt;/title&gt;&lt;p&gt;This is a testcase&lt;/p&gt;"
"</userinput>. This will produce exactly the same output as if the content "
"had been loaded from a document of its own."

#. Tag: para
#: index.docbook:40
#, fuzzy, no-c-format
#| msgid ""
#| "Specifying alternate character sets is also possible. Note that 8-Bit "
#| "characters have to be escaped by a percentage sign and their two-digit "
#| "hexadecimal codes: <userinput>data:;charset=iso-8859-1,Gr%FC%DFe aus Schl"
#| "%E4gl</userinput> results in <literal>Gr&uuml;&szlig;e aus Schl&auml;gl</"
#| "literal> whereas omitting the charset attribute might lead to something "
#| "like <literal>Gr??e aus Schl?gl</literal>"
msgid ""
"Specifying alternate character sets is also possible. Note that 8-Bit "
"characters have to be escaped by a percentage sign and their two-digit "
"hexadecimal codes: <quote><userinput>data:;charset=iso-8859-1,Gr%FC%DFe aus "
"Schl%E4gl</userinput></quote> results in <quote><literal>Gr&uuml;&szlig;e "
"aus Schl&auml;gl</literal></quote> whereas omitting the charset attribute "
"might lead to something like <quote><literal>Gr??e aus Schl?gl</literal></"
"quote>."
msgstr ""
"Specifying alternate character sets is also possible. Note that 8-Bit "
"characters have to be escaped by a percentage sign and their two-digit "
"hexadecimal codes: <userinput>data:;charset=iso-8859-1,Gr%FC%DFe aus Schl"
"%E4gl</userinput> results in <literal>Gr&uuml;&szlig;e aus Schl&auml;gl</"
"literal> whereas omitting the charset attribute might lead to something like "
"<literal>Gr??e aus Schl?gl</literal>"

